isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.56) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.26. The model’s intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.53 (S.E. = 0.27, p < .001, 95% CI [13.01, 14.05]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.13, S.E. = 0.38, p = 0.733, 95% CI [-0.87, 0.61]; Std. beta = -0.03, 95% CI [-0.21, 0.15])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.52, S.E. = 0.35, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.21, -1.82]; Std. beta = -0.61, 95% CI [-0.77, -0.44])
  • The effect of time point [3rd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -1.02, S.E. = 1.12, p = 0.364, 95% CI [-3.21, 1.18]; Std. beta = -0.24, 95% CI [-0.77, 0.28])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.96, S.E. = 0.52, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.98, -1.93]; Std. beta = -0.71, 95% CI [-0.96, -0.47])
  • The interaction effect of time point [3rd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -4.64, S.E. = 1.47, p = 0.002, 95% CI [-7.53, -1.75]; Std. beta = -1.12, 95% CI [-1.81, -0.42])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
